
# geogridmap

geogrid map is a python module for plotting a probability density map from a gaussian mixture model over a geographic map

## Installation
Use the package manager [pip](https://pip.pypa.io/en/stable/) to install geogridmap.

```bash
pip install geogridmap
```

## Usage

An example of geogridmap in action.

First lets define a gaussian mixture model with 3 centroids in the city of London


```python
import geogridmap as ggm
import numpy as np

np.random.seed(2)

london = [51.507, -0.1278]

london_means = ggm.random_centroid_maker(london, [0.002, 0.002], 3) #generating centroids randomly
london_vars = np.array([[0.001, 0.001],[0.001, 0.001], [0.001,0.001]]) #defining variances (no covariances)
london_weights = np.array([0.3, 0.3, 0.4]) #defining the weights

london_gmm = ggm.gmm(london_means,london_vars, london_weights)
```

### Visualising the defined centroids over the city of london


```python
london_map = ggm.prob_map(location = london, zoom = 10)

#The plot ploints function can only handle tuples 

mean_plot = []
for mean in london_means:
    lat = mean[0]
    long = mean[1]
    
    mean_plot.append((lat, long))
    
london_map.plot_points(mean_plot, color = 'blue')
```

### Visualising samples from the gmm over the city of london


```python
london_samples = london_gmm.sampler(30)

london_map.plot_points(london_samples, color = 'red', radius = 3)
```

### Visualising a heatmap


```python
london_map.heat_map(points = london_samples, radius = 1)
```

### Visualising the  probability distribution on the map


```python
london_map_prob = ggm.prob_map(location = london, zoom = 10)

#Defining the borders of the grid and the number of squares in each row/column
vert = 0.1
horiz = 0.15

london_map_prob.grid(north = london[0] + vert, south = london[0] - vert, 
                 east = london[1] + horiz, west = london[1] - horiz, squares = 3, gmm = london_gmm)

london_map_prob.grid_plot(boundaries = [0, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3, 1], colors = ['blue','red' ,'yellow', 'green'])
```

## Calculating the cdf value of points i.e. the density to the bottom left of a given point


```python
oxford_circus = [51.5152, -0.1419]

london_gmm.cdf(oxford_circus)
```




    0.39464875078949113



Therefore roughly 40% of the area of the density is to the South West of Oxford Circus.

Calculating the medians of the distribution along the latitude and longitude dimension


```python
london_gmm.inverse_cdf(0.5, direction = 'latitude')
```




    51.43662422784027




```python
london_gmm.inverse_cdf(0.5, direction = 'longitude')
```




    -0.13018016358854717
